The paper deals with the computational complexity of gerrymandering, which involves partitioning problems and optimization. This suggests that it could belong to several sub-categories, including cs.CC (computational complexity), cs.DS (data structures and algorithms), cs.CG (computational geometry), cs.GT (computational game theory), and cs.SI (social and information networks). Among these, cs.CC and cs.DS are the most likely categories, as they deal directly with computational complexity and algorithms. However, cs.CG and cs.GT are also relevant due to the geometric and game-theoretic aspects of gerrymandering, while cs.SI could be relevant due to the social and network-based implications of gerrymandering.
